{"key":"post-16299736","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>16299736</id>\n<content>There's so much bad info above it made my head spin, but at least a couple got it right.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Your problem is not humidity, it is fresh air exchange.&amp;nbsp; If your humidity was in the 60s, you would have no fruits, so you're yet another victim of made in china crap they call hygrometers.&amp;nbsp; They don't work, as we've known for years.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Air entering your terrarium does not lower humidity.&amp;nbsp; If you have a proper shotgun terrarium elevated on blocks, air enters the bottom, passes through the perlite, exchanging air and humidifying the terrarium at the same time.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The problem in closets is there is no natural circulation, thus terrariums don't work properly.&amp;nbsp; Move the terrarium to a table in an open room.&amp;nbsp; Don't run fans or such in the room either.&amp;nbsp; The shotgun terrarium depends on the natural circulation present.&amp;nbsp; Leave a window slightly open for best results.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next></next>\n<prev>16299646</prev>\n<first>16298223</first>\n<last>16299736</last>\n<when>1338296328</when>\n<utime>05/29/12 03:58 PM</utime>\n</post>"}